{"findings":[{"id":"F-001","severity":"High","confidence":"high","title":"Zero-value `transferFrom` lets anyone tamper with another user's pressure accounting and force release/halving","locations":["0x35a254223960c18b69c0526c46b013d022e93902/Contract.sol:ERC20.sol:70","0x35a254223960c18b69c0526c46b013d022e93902/Contract.sol:UpSwing.sol:157","0x35a254223960c18b69c0526c46b013d022e93902/Contract.sol:UpSwing.sol:165","0x35a254223960c18b69c0526c46b013d022e93902/Contract.sol:UpSwing.sol:171","0x35a254223960c18b69c0526c46b013d022e93902/Contract.sol:UpSwing.sol:124"],"claim":"`ERC20.transferFrom()` calls `_transfer()` before subtracting allowance, and subtracting an allowance by `0` succeeds even when no approval exists. UpSwing's overridden `_transfer()` has non-standard side effects even for zero-amount transfers: `transferFrom(victim, UNIv2, 0)` increments `txCount[victim]`, and `transferFrom(victim, victim, 0)` reaches `releasePressure(victim)`. Because `releasePressure()` either settles the user's pending pressure or halves it when the computed burn exceeds pair liquidity, any third party can permissionlessly mutate another account's pressure lifecycle.","impact":"An attacker can grief traders at near-zero cost. Repeated zero-value `transferFrom(victim, UNIv2, 0)` calls can push `txCount[victim]` arbitrarily high, making future sells accrue negligible `sellPressure`. Separately, `transferFrom(victim, victim, 0)` can force an early settlement or a punitive halving of the victim's pending pressure based on current market conditions, and also triggers a liquidity-pool burn/sync when settlement succeeds.","paths":["After trading is unpaused, call `transferFrom(victim, UNIv2, 0)` repeatedly; no approval is needed because allowance is reduced by zero, but `txCount[victim]` still increments.","When `victim` has pending pressure, call `transferFrom(victim, victim, 0)`; this invokes `releasePressure(victim)`, which either settles immediately if the computed amount is below pair balance or halves `sellPressure[victim]` if the amount is larger than pair liquidity."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-002","severity":"Medium","confidence":"medium","title":"Pressure settlement uses manipulable spot pair balance and total supply instead of sale-time state","locations":["0x35a254223960c18b69c0526c46b013d022e93902/Contract.sol:UpSwing.sol:100","0x35a254223960c18b69c0526c46b013d022e93902/Contract.sol:UpSwing.sol:120","0x35a254223960c18b69c0526c46b013d022e93902/Contract.sol:UpSwing.sol:124","0x35a254223960c18b69c0526c46b013d022e93902/Contract.sol:UpSwing.sol:176"],"claim":"`releasePressure()` computes the burn/mint amount from `amountPressure(sellPressure[user])`, and `amountPressure()` reads `balanceOf(UNIv2)` and `totalSupply()` at release time. Neither value is snapshotted when the sell pressure is created, so the eventual payout depends on mutable spot state rather than the state that produced the pressure.","impact":"A trader or MEV searcher can change another user's pending burn and Steam payout just before forcing release. Moving UPS into or out of the pair changes `balanceOf(UNIv2)`, and any holder can call `burn()` to reduce `totalSupply()`. Combined with the zero-value forced-release primitive, this makes user payouts and pair burns manipulable at settlement time, enabling unfair reward changes and price manipulation around `sync()`.","paths":["Let a target accumulate `sellPressure`, then alter the pair's UPS balance via trades or direct token transfers and immediately force `releasePressure(target)` with `transferFrom(target, target, 0)`.","Burn UPS before forcing another user's release; the reduced `totalSupply()` increases the computed ratio inside `amountPressure()`, changing how much is burned from the pair and minted as Steam."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]},{"id":"F-003","severity":"Low","confidence":"high","title":"Sell transfers emit a `Transfer` value that does not match actual balance changes","locations":["0x35a254223960c18b69c0526c46b013d022e93902/Contract.sol:UpSwing.sol:162","0x35a254223960c18b69c0526c46b013d022e93902/Contract.sol:UpSwing.sol:167","0x35a254223960c18b69c0526c46b013d022e93902/Contract.sol:UpSwing.sol:173"],"claim":"In `_transfer()`, sender and recipient balances are updated using the original `amount`, but when `recipient == UNIv2` the local `amount` variable is later reduced by `UPSMath(txCount[sender])` before the `Transfer` event is emitted. The logged event therefore reports a smaller amount than the number of UPS tokens that actually moved.","impact":"Off-chain systems and on-chain integrations that infer transfers from events can become desynchronized from real balances, leading to incorrect accounting, analytics, or reward attribution around sells to the pair.","paths":["Sell UPS to `UNIv2`; storage credits the pair with the full token amount, while the emitted `Transfer` event logs only the discounted post-`UPSMath` amount."],"round":1,"source_agents":["codex_1"]}],"rejected_candidates":[{"title":"Unauthorized Steam Token Minting via Owner Privileges","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"False positive: `Steam` is deployed via `new Steam(...)` inside `UpSwing`, so `Steam._UPS` is the `UpSwing` contract address, not the external deployer."},{"title":"Centralized Admin Control with No Timelock","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"This is a governance/trust assumption, not a distinct code vulnerability in the permissionless protocol logic."},{"title":"Missing Zero Address Validation in setUNIv2","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Requires privileged misconfiguration by an allowed address; it does not create an independent permissionless exploit beyond trusted-admin control."},{"title":"Division by Zero in amountPressure","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Only reachable if all UPS supply is voluntarily burned away; that is a terminal self-destruction scenario rather than a realistic independent protocol bug."},{"title":"Reentrancy Vulnerability in _transfer","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"The only external call is `sync()` on the configured pair; exploiting reentrancy would require a privileged actor to point `UNIv2` at a malicious contract, so this is not an independent permissionless issue."},{"title":"Integer Overflow in amountPressure with High Leverage","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"False positive: arithmetic uses `SafeMath`, and `leverage` is a `uint8`, so the proposed >1000 overflow path is not valid."},{"title":"Missing Event Emissions for Critical Functions","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Transparency issue only; not a realistic protocol-security vulnerability."},{"title":"Leverage Can Be Set to Zero Breaking Protocol","source_agents":["opencode_1"],"reason":"Relies entirely on privileged admin action and is covered by the protocol's trusted-admin model rather than an exploitable bug."}]}
